==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Etiolate
<hw>E"ti*o*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Etiolated</conjf> <pr>(#)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n</pos>. <conjf>Etiolating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧tioler</ets> to blanch.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become
white or whiter; to be whitened or blanched by excluding the light of
the sun, as, plants.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>To become pale through disease or
absence of light.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Etiolate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Etiolate
<hw>E"ti*o*late</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To blanch; to
bleach; to whiten by depriving of the sun's rays.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>To cause to grow pale by disease
or absence of light.</def></p>

<p><ent>Etiolated</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Etiolate</ent>⟦br⟧
